Messalla means that the vast interval (‘ infinita differentia', above) that separates the rhetoric of the present day from the golden age of Roman ora- tory finds a parallel in Greece : it is even more noticeable there, he sayS, if yon

consider Demosthenes and the rhetoricians of Asia Minor on the one hand, and on the other Cicero and the foremost orators of our own time. To his mind this only makes the phenomenon all the more remarkable and its 'explanation more difficult (auget quaestionem).
